<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Velayati Meets Kuwaiti, Syrian Counterparts </H4>

<F P=102> LD0206095094 Tehran IRNA in English 0832 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, June 2, IRNA -- Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali 
Akbar Velayati here Wednesday [1 June] discussed bilateral, 
regional and international issues in separate meetings with his 
Kuwaiti, Syrian and Indian counterparts. 
  Velayati, who is here to attend the four-day Non-Aligned 
Movement (NAM) ministerial meeting, and his Kuwaiti counterpart, 
Shaykh sabah al-Ahmad al-Sabah, in a meeting stressed the 
importance of bilateral relations as well as speeding up of the 
formation of Iran-Kuwait joint economic commission. 
  Describing the recent visit of a group of Kuwati University 
professors and journalists to Tehran as "positive", Velayati 
said that it could pave the way for further enhancing mutual 
understanding between the two countries. 
  He also referred to the Kuwait-Iraq relations and expressed 
hope that the two can find peaceful ways to solve their border 
disputes by preventing further interference of the foreign 
powers in the region. 
  Pointing out to the latest developments in Kuwait-Iraq 
relations, Al-Sabah stressed the need for full implementation of 
the U.N. Security Council's resolutions on Iraq. He also 
expressed willingness to visit Iran in a near future to explore 
avenues for further promotion of bilateral ties. 
  Meanwhile, in another meeting Velayati and his Syrian 
counterpart Faruq al-Shar' stressed the need for holding the 
tripartite meeting by Iran, Syria and Turkey due to be held in 
Damascus next summer. 
  The two sides also exchanged views on the issue of Palestine 
and the expansionist policies of the Zionist regime. 
  Earlier in the day, Velayati met with his Indian counterpart 
Dinesh Singh and discussed Tehran-New Delhi relations, latest 
developments in Kashmir and the issues pertaining the NAM 
meeting. 
  Velayati arrived here last Monday heading a ranking 
delegation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

