<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on Velayati-al-Sabah Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> NC0106210894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1950 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0106210894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 1 Jun (MENA) -- Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad 
al-Sabah, Kuwaiti deputy prime minister and foreign minister, 
and Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali Akbar Velayati met this 
evening on the sideline of the ministerial Non-Aligned 
Conference in Cairo. 
  Shaykh al-Sabah said they exchanged views on a number of 
issues, including Iraq-Kuwait relations and the ties between 
Kuwait and Iran, which he described as good. 
  He noted that the Iranian president invited Shaykh Jabir 
al-Ahmad, amir of Kuwait, to visit Tehran. He said the visit 
will take place very soon. 
  When asked about the altercation between the Kuwaiti and 
Iraqi delegations today, Shaykh al-Sabah said the Kuwaiti 
delegation was replying to the remarks of the Iraqi delegation 
concerning the Security Council resolutions that Kuwait, along 
with the entire world, demands be implemented. Regrettably, he 
said, Iraq always says that it closed the file the Kuwait issue. 
  If Iraq really means that, the Kuwaiti minister said, then 
the Iraqi Government and National Assembly should send an 
official document to the Security Council telling it that they 
accept all its resolutions. 
  He denied any Egyptian mediation to improve relations 
between 
Iraq and Kuwait. 
  The Iranian foreign minister was asked about Iran's future 
relations with the PLO in light of Iran's opposition to the 
Palestinian-Israeli agreement. He replied that the PLO still 
operates its embassy in Tehran, and that the Iranian Government 
has good ties with the various Palestinian factions. He said 
his country is sympathetic toward the Palestinian cause, and it 
closed the Israeli embassy and replaced it with an embassy for 
Palestine. 
  Velayati said there are plans for the presidents of Iran and 
Syria to meet in Damascus in July to discuss regional and 
international issues of mutual concern. The presidents will 
also discuss the situation in northern Iraq, which is called the 
Kurdish region, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

