<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on Velayti-al-Shar' Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> NC0106193194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1810 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0106193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 1 Jun (MENA) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Faruq 
al-Shar' and Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali Akbar Velayati met in 
Cairo this afternoon on the sidelines of the 11th Non-Aligned 
ministerial conference. 
  Velayati told reporters after the one-hour meeting that the 
talks were good and constructive, and that they discussed 
bilateral relations and the topics on the agenda of the 
non-aligned conference. 
  He said they also discussed the subjects that will be 
brought 
before the next meeting in Damascus attended by Syria, Turkey 
and Iran at the end of July concerning the situation in northern 
Iraq. 
  Velayati said he will meet with his Kuwaiti counterpart 
Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad al-Sabah, and will take part in the 
meeting of the liaison group of the Islamic Conference 
Organization on Bosnia. 
  For his part, Syrian Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' said 
after the meeting that he and Velayati discussed bilateral 
relations and a number of issues of mutual concern. He 
described the Syrian-Iranian relations as cordial and said the 
two countries are exchanging views. 
  Al-Shar' said it is intended to hold a summit meeting among 
the presidents of Syria, Turkey, and Iran in Damascus in July to 
discuss ties and issues of common concern. 
  On the Middle East peace process, al-Shar' said no progress 
has been made in the Syrian-Israeli negotiations because of 
Israel's intransigence. There is no peace between Israel and 
Syria now, he said. 
  Asked about Israel's abduction of Lebanese resistance leader 
Mustafa al-Dirani, the Syrian minister said this is an act of 
piracy and terrorism. He said the abduction is a violation of 
Lebanese sovereignty and an act of international terrorism. He 
said resistance in southern Lebanon is a legitimate right which 
Syria supports. 

</TEXT>

