<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Velayati Holds Talks With Omani Minister </H4>

<F P=102> NC0106132894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1220 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0106132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 1 Jun (MENA) -- Omani Minister of State for 
Foreign Affairs Yusuf Bin-'Alawi Bin-'Abdallah has said that his 
country and Iran will work together to establish peace and 
stability in the Gulf region. 
  Following his meeting with Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali 
Akbar Velayati today, Bin-'Alawi told MENA that he and the 
Iranian minister discussed several important issues, including 
the situation in Yemen, Bosnia-Herzegovina, and the Gulf region 
in addition to bilateral ties. 
  Touching on the Gulf security arrangements, Bin-'Alawi 
explained that this issue was not discussed during the meeting. 
Our stance is clear in this connection, he said, noting that 
his meeting with the Iranian minister focused primarily on the 
issues included on the agenda of the Non-Aligned Movement 
Conference. 
  The Omani state minister emphasized that a cease-fire in 
Yemen will give Yemenis the chance to return to negotiations and 
decide their country's future. 
  Replying to a question on relations between the Sultanate of 
Oman and Israel, Bin-'Alawi said that there are no relations 
between his country and Israel and that the Israeli delegation 
that visited Muscat recently only took part in the multilateral 
negotiations. This does not mean that there are Omani-Israeli 
relations, he said. 
  I clearly explained that the establishment of such relations 
in the future means that Israel will have to withdraw from all 
the occupied Arab territories and that a comprehensive peace 
will have to be established between Israel and all Arab states, 
he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

