<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers Hold Sideline Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Al-Shar' Meets DPRK, RSA Ministers </H4>

<F P=102> JN0106165894 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 1515 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0106165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo -- On the sidelines of the meetings of the 
11th Non-Aligned foreign ministers' conference, [Syrian] Foreign 
Minister Faruq al-Shar' today met with Talal Sat'an al-Hasan, 
Jordanian minister of state for foreign affairs. 
  The talks dealt with the Middle East peace process and its 
developments. The talks also dealt with the issues listed on 
the agenda of the Non-Aligned Conference. 
  Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' also met with Kim Yong-nam, 
vice premier and foreign minister of the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea. 
  During the meeting, the two sides exchanged views on issues 
listed on the agenda of the conference. The talks also dealt 
with relations between the two friendly countries. 
  Faruq al-Shar' also met with South African Foreign Minister 
Alfred Nzo. Al-Shar' congratulated the South African foreign 
minister on his country's joining of the Non-Aligned Movement. 
He said that the lifting of apartheid is a victory for the 
movement and mankind in general. 
  During the meeting, the two sides expressed their concern 
for 
establishing firm relations between the two countries in all 
fields. 
  The South African foreign minister highly appreciated 
Syria's 
support for the just struggle of the African National Congress 
and its historic success in dismantling the apartheid system and 
establishing a nonracial democratic republic. 
  The foreign minister also met with Bosnian Foreign Minister 
Dr. Irfan Ljubijankic. The talks dealt with the developments in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Al-Shar' met with Professor Guido De Marco, Maltese deputy 
prime minister and foreign minister. 
  During the meeting, the talks dealt with the situation in 
the 
region, and latest developments in the Middle East peace process. 

</TEXT>

