<F P=100> EGYPT </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim Brotherhood Denies Link With Lawyers Demonstration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslim Brotherhood Denies Link With Lawyers Demonstration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0106200694 Cairo AL-'ARABI in Arabic 30 May 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> NC0106200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-'ARABI </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Khalid Salah and 'Abd-al-Fattah 'Abd-al-Mun'im] </F>
  [Excerpts] Diya'-al-Din Dawud, secretary general of the 
Nasirite Arab Democratic Party and People's Assembly member, on 
Sunday presented an urgent enquiry to the prime minister and the 
interior minister on the recent incidents in the Lawyers 
Association and the circumstances surrounding the mysterious 
death of lawyer 'Abd-al-Harith Madani. [passage omitted] 
  The incidents at the Lawyers Association continue to draw 
political reactions. Within the attempts of the Muslim 
Brotherhood to avoid a clash with the government--a clash that 
appeared increasingly likely in the past weeks--Muslim 
Brotherhood General Guide Muhammad Hamid Abu-al-Nasr has denied 
any responsibility for his group in stirring up and leading the 
demonstration that was staged by the lawyers a few weeks ago to 
protest the death of lawyer 'Abd-al-Harith Madani hours after 
his arrest late last month. 
  In statements to AL-'ARABI, Abu-al-Nasr said the Muslim 
Brotherhood was falsely blamed for the Lawyers Association 
incidents. He said the Muslim Brotherhood "has nothing to do 
with the associations and does not interfere in their affairs!" 
He explained the attacks on the Muslim Brotherhood in the 
government media as a continuation of statements President 
Mubarak made to the German magazine DER SPIEGEL, in which he 
accused the banned Muslim Brotherhood of supporting terrorism. 
Following those statements by the president, Abu-al-Nasr said, 
the official media "rushed to launch a strong attack against us, 
and even blamed us for the Lawyers Association incidents!" 
  Security forces yesterday arrested five Muslim Brotherhood 
members. They were referred to the prosecution, which decided 
to remand them for two weeks for interrogation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35602 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes106_c_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-106 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

