<H3> <TI>   Information Minister on New Television Channels </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Information Minister on New Television Channels </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2705135494 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1130 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2705135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] As part of celebrations marking media day, 
President Husni Mubarak will inaugurate Channel Three of the 
central delta on Monday. The channel will begin experimental 
transmission for four hours per day, gradually increasing to 
eight hours per day in June, until it finally reaches full 
transmission in October. 
  Information Minister Safwat al-Sharif has stated that 
Channel 
Seven will begin transmission in al-Minya in President Mubarak's 
presence. The president inaugurated the first stage of that 
project last October. 
  As for the Egyptian international channel, Nile TV, the 
information minister said that it transmits two hours daily at 
present. This will be increased to six hours, using the 
European satellite [not further specified]. He added that 
preparations are underway to expand this channel to African 
areas via Arabsat by the end of 1994. [passage omitted] 
  Al-Sharif added that a strategic project will be submitted 
to 
President Mubarak. This project is the Egyptian satellite, for 
which studies have been completed by French and U.S. firms. The 
satellite will have between 12 and 56 channels. Al-Sharif hopes 
that work on the project will start before the end of this year 
so that the satellite can be launched by the end of 1996. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

