<H3> <TI>   Tunisian Prime Minister Arrives in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tunisian Prime Minister Arrives in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2805093994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0845 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2805093994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 28 May (MENA)--Tunisian Prime Minister Dr. 
Hamed Karoui arrived in Cairo today on a two-day official visit 
to Egypt. 
  On his arrival, Karoui stated that he was carrying a message 
from Tunisian President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali to President 
Muhammad Husni Mubarak. The message is part of the continuous 
consultations between the leaders on bilateral relations, Arab 
and Middle East issues, and the African summit, which is 
scheduled to convene in Tunis in June. 
  Karoui said he will inform President Mubarak of the Tunisian 
president's views and will hear President Mubarak's views on 
African and international issues. 
  Answering a question on the situation in Yemen, he said that 
developments there are regrettable. He added: We were hoping 
to put the Arab house in order, but we haven't lost hope yet. 
We would like the United Nations to resolve this issue despite 
the fact that there are numerous issues that the United Nations 
has not been able to resolve. We hope the brothers in Yemen 
will manage to find a way to unite once again. 
  Karoui refused to comment on the secession of south Yemen. 
He expressed his hope that the Yemenis will find a solution 
amongst themselves. 
  The Tunisian prime minister concluded his statement by 
saying 
that his country will take part in the conference of the 
Nonaligned countries' foreign ministers scheduled to convene in 
Cairo on Tuesday [31 May]. 
  Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa greeted Karoui upon his arrival. 

</TEXT>

