<F P=100> EGYPT </F>
<H3> <TI>   Loan Signed To Develop Private Small Industries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Loan Signed To Develop Private Small Industries </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0106161294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1230 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0106161294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 1 Jun (MENA)-- Egypt and the European 
Investment Bank [EIB] have signed an agreement granting Egypt a 
120-million-pound loan to be allocated completely to private 
small industries. 
  Dr. Yusuf Butrus Ghali, minister of state for international 
cooperation, and EIB Deputy Director Robert Dillon signed the 
agreement. 
  Dr. Ghali pointed out that the agreement is within the 
context of the government's efforts to consolidate the private 
sector and emphasize its crucial role in economic development in 
Egypt. He added that the loan is a significant first step in 
the government's efforts to guarantee the provision of the 
financial instruments needed for developing the private sector, 
like long-term and easy loans to suit small industries employing 
a maximum of 10 workers. He remarked that small industries are 
the backbone of the policy that aims to increase production and 
employment rates. 

</TEXT>

