<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Reiterates Rejection of UN `Interference' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Reiterates Rejection of UN `Interference' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0106181694 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0106181694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Prime Minister brother 'Abd-al-Wahhab 
al-Anisi has reaffirmed that the war, which was triggered by the 
gang of apostasy and secession in the Yemeni Socialist Party 
leadership, is between the Yemeni people and a mutinous group 
violating the constitutional legitimacy. 
  Referring to the concern of the brothers and friends, as 
well 
as their calls for halting the fighting, he wondered: On what 
basis do they call for a cease-fire, and what are the guarantees 
that the rebels would resort to the constitutional legitimacy 
and its institutions, which were established as a result of the 
general elections that were held on 27 April 1993 and that were 
(?defined) by everybody. 
  The deputy prime minister reiterated our country's rejection 
of any interference in its domestic affairs by the Security 
Council or any other side, stressing that what is taking place 
in the Republic of Yemen is an internal affair. He also voiced 
his surprise at some brothers' insistence on the need for the 
Security Council to issue a resolution on a cease-fire, although 
they know that the issue belongs to the Yemeni people alone. 
Such a resolution, he added, will lead to more fighting, which 
is sought by those who want such a resolution. 
  This came during a news conference he gave at the Prime 
Ministry today. Several representatives of local, Arab, and 
international television networks, radio stations, and press in 
Sanaa attended. It was also attended by 'Abd-al-Rahman Zaydan, 
director of the prime minister's office, and [name indistinct], 
under secretary of the Ministry of Information. 

</TEXT>

