<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Questions Fate of Pro-YSP Abu-Luhum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Report Questions Fate of Pro-YSP Abu-Luhum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0106141894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 30 May 94 p1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0106141894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Questions About Fate of Shaykh Sinan </F>
Abu-Luhum"] 
  [Text] London, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Various reports have 
been circulating in Yemeni political circles and in diplomatic 
circles about the fate of Shaykh Sinan Abu-Luhum, leader of the 
Popular Forces Union and a senior chieftain of the Bakil tribes 
who is known for his opposition to President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih and his sympathy with the positions and policy of the 
Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] throughout the years of Yemeni 
unity. 
  Informed sources note that Shaykh Abu-Luhum has disappeared 
from the arena in recent weeks, since his return to Sanaa at the 
beginning of the Yemeni war. Despite his state of health and 
advanced age, he had made great efforts in bridging the views of 
Yemeni president and his Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid since 
the beginning of the crisis last August. 
  The sources say that Abu-Luhum may be under house arrest at 
present for refusing to add his name to the list of supporters 
signed by a number of YSP and opposition leaders currently in 
Sanaa despite their known opposition to President Salih in the 
past. 
  It is worth noting that commercial offices partly owned by 
Shaykh Sinan were burned down six week ago while he was in the 
United States for medical treatment, because of the positions he 
had taken and statements he made to Sanaa's dissatisfaction, 
particularly his support for a strong Arab role in settling the 
Yemeni crisis after the Sanaa and Aden officials failed to 
contain that crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

