<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Elaborates Stance on Abu Musa Islands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Elaborates Stance on Abu Musa Islands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206082394 Tehran IRNA in English 0741 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0206082394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, June 2, (IRNA) -- A Foreign Ministry 
spokesman here Thursday [2 June] reiterated Iran's policy of 
establishing friendly ties with the Persian Gulf states and said 
the country is ready to hold direct and bilateral talks with the 
United Arab Emirates [UAE] to eliminate the existing 
misunderstandings. 
  The spokesman, Mahmud Mohammadi, was referring to the recent 
statements by the UAE Crown Prince Shaykh Khalifah Bin-Zayid Al 
Nuhayyan who has called for the establishment of friendly ties 
with Tehran but asked Iran to give up the three islands of Abu 
Musa, the Lesser and the Greater Tonbs. 
  Mohammadi further added that the Islamic Republic of Iran 
attaches great importance to the security and stability of the 
region. 
  He stressed that Iran had always tried to maintain security 
and stability in the region and under critical conditions had 
even welcomed cooperation of other countries in thwarting 
threats against the collective regional interests. 
  The spokesman said that Shaykh Khalifah's statements 
regarding the three Iranian islands were in contradiction with 
the UAE's call for the establishment of friendly ties with Iran. 
  Mohammadi termed as incorrect the report aired by Agence 
France Presse (AFP) on the meeting between the Iranian and 
Egyptian Foreign ministers in the course of the on-going 
Non-alignment Movement [NAM] ministerial session, convened in 
Cairo Tuesday. 
  AFP had reported that Egyptian Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
had 
expressed willingness to confer with his Iranian counterpart 
'Ali Akbar Velayati and quoted Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman 
as saying that Velayati would not meet any Egyptian official. 
  He said that to meet with foreign ministers of other 
countries at multilateral sessions and holding talks with them 
is quite customary. 
  Stressing that Iran and Egypt are two influential members of 
the movement, the spokesman said that during the NAM meeting the 
two foreign ministers can discuss major issues such as situation 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina, disarmament and restructuring of the U.N. 
organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

