<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Report on Military Budgets, Subsidies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    * Report on Military Budgets, Subsidies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94LA0168B Stockholm NAMEH-YE MARDOM in Persian 12 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> 94LA0168B </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm NAMEH-YE MARDOM </F>
<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] By cutting more than 15 percent of the revenues and 
expenditures recommended by the government, the Majles has 
approved the 1373 [21 March 1994- 20 March 1995] budget bill. 
Most of the government's current and general expenses have been 
reduced compared to the year 1372 [21 March 1993-20 March 1994]. 
The defense budget was the only section whose increase the 
Majles did not oppose, increasing it by $850 million to $1.4 
billion while decreasing food subsidies from $1.2 billion to 
$800 million. 
  The first effect of the approved budget came before the 
beginning of the new year. The "Railroad of the Islamic 
Republic" increased by 30 to 50 percent ticket prices for 
various passenger trains during the New Year's holidays on the 
pretext of the "cutoff in government aid and subsidies." Then in 
the first days of the new year it announced that the new ticket 
prices would be permanent. 

</TEXT>

