<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   11th Conference of Non-Aligned Countries Resumes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    11th Conference of Non-Aligned Countries Resumes </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Musa Reviews Agenda </H4>

<F P=102> NC0106161194 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1130 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0106161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The 11th ministerial conference of the non-aligned 
countries resumed its meetings today with the heads of 
delegations at the conference hall in Madinat al-Nasr in Cairo 
under the chairmanship of Egyptian Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa. 
  The General Ministerial Committee resumed its discussion of 
the items on the agenda: disarmament, international security, 
the double standards from which developing states are suffering 
at the international level, and the possibility of expanding 
membership of the UN Security Council to include a larger number 
of Third World states. 
  The political and economic committees began their meetings. 
The Economic Committee will discuss the impact of GATT on 
developing countries' economies and the problem of African debt. 
  Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa stated that at its morning 
session, the conference discussed a report by the Non-Aligned 
Movement's chairman on the political and economic problems 
facing the movement. He added that the afternoon session will 
discuss the UN role, its reorganization, and the international 
economic situation, with emphasis on GATT and its impact on 
Third World economies. He added that the conference will also 
discuss the social development of the non-aligned states as well 
as the venue for the next non-aligned summit. He said that a 
Latin American state will probably host that summit. Musa 
revealed that the conference will also discuss the setting up of 
a mechanism to handle disputes among the movement members. 
  Asked about differences emerging during the present meeting, 
Musa said that there are no disputes other than that between 
Iraq and Kuwait. He said that he met with the Saudi, Syrian, 
and other Arab foreign ministers today and discussed 
developments in Yemen, since events there affect the entire 
region. He added that the continuation of military operations 
is of concern to all Arabs. 
  Musa said that Egypt will certainly approve the resolution 
that the UN Security Council will issue. He explained that this 
resolution will call for an end to the fighting and for 
dispatching a fact-finding committee to Yemen. He noted that 
Egypt was among the cosponsors of that draft resolution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

