<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Missile Injures 21 in Aden After Cease-Fire Call </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Missile Injures 21 in Aden After Cease-Fire Call </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0206100294 Paris AFP in English 0829 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0206100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Aden, Yemen, June 2 (AFP) -- A missile fired by 
northern Yemeni forces slammed into this southern stronghold on 
Thursday [2 June] wounding 21 people and artillery duels raged 
only hours after the UN Security Council called for a ceasefire. 
  One of two surface-to-surface missiles was intercepted by 
south Yemeni anti-aircraft fire but the other exploded near a 
mosque in the northern suburb of al-Shaykh 'Uthman, officials 
said. 
  Sixteen worshipers were hurt inside the mosque when the 
missile struck during dawn prayers. The raid left pools of 
blood on the carpets and the courtyard, witnesses said. Five 
people were injured in nearby dwellings. 
  Hundreds later gathered in the area to denounce "the killer 
regime" of President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, a northerner. 
  The missile attack came just hours after the United Nations 
Security Council had adopted a resolution calling for a 
ceasefire in the civil war in Yemen, which erupted May 5. 
  Heavy artillery duels on the war front just north of Aden 
were so intense Thursday morning that buildings in the city 
shook heavily. 
  Southern warplanes were constantly taking off and landing at 
Aden Airport as they flew sorties against the northern forces of 
Salih, who has strongly opposed any UN "interference" in the 
conflict. 
  The presidential council of the breakaway southern state led 
by 'Ali Salim al-Bid announced it would "unconditionally 
respect" the Security Council resolution and assist a fact 
finding mission being dispatched by the world body. 
  There was no immediate reaction from Sanaa, where the 
government held a meeting to discuss the resolution. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35710 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes106_v_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-106 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leghari on Foreign Investment, Nuclear Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leghari on Foreign Investment, Nuclear Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0106145694 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0106145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Farooq Ahmad Khan Leghari has said, as a 
result of sound economic policies adopted by the present 
government, the climate for foreign investment in Pakistan has 
become lucrative. The president was addressing Pakistanis in New 
York. The president said the response of foreign investors to 
the government's incentive package has been very positive. As a 
result of macroeconomic management, foreign investment in 
several sectors -- particularly in the sector of power 
generation -- will increase in the days to come. 
  He said Pakistan's nuclear program is not weapon-oriented. 
We have taken a conscious decision not to use our nuclear 
capability for weapon production unless our security is 
threatened. The president said Pakistan has told the United 
States that no unilateral solution could be imposed on Pakistan. 
Any solution to the nonproliferation problem in South Asian 
region has to be evolved in the regional context. He said 
Pakistan had proposed in 1974 that the South Asian region be 
declared a nuclear-free zone. Since then, Pakistan has made six 
more concrete proposals to achieve nonproliferation in the 
region, but India has rejected all of them. Under the 
circumstances, the United States or the world at large could not 
expect realistically that Pakistan would accept any unilateral 
obligation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

