<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Iraq's al-Sahhaf Meets Indian Minister </H4>

<F P=102> JN0206111694 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0817 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0206111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 Jun (INA) -- [Iraqi] Foreign Minister 
Muhammad Sa'id al-Sahhaf met here today with Lal Bhatia, the 
Indian minister of state for external affairs. 
  The foreign minister briefed his Indian counterpart on the 
positive stands that prevailed at the recent UN Security Council 
discussions concerning the lifting of the embargo clamped on 
Iraq, and on the majority that called for taking measures to 
lift the embargo as long as Iraq has implemented Resolution 687. 
  The talks dealt with relations between Iraq and India, means 
of promoting them, and coordination between them. The two 
ministers stressed the importance of reactivating the Nonaligned 
Movement's role in international relations, of maintaining the 
spirit and essence of the movement's principles, and of 
reinforcing economic relations among its member states. 
  Foreign Minister Muhammad Sa'id al-Sahhaf also met with 
Cypriot Foreign Minister Alexandros Mikhailidhis. 
  The foreign minister explained the positive stands at the 
recent UN Security Council discussions, which have clearly shown 
that Iraq has implemented all the UN Security Council 
resolutions, and that what remains is a resolution to lift the 
embargo imposed on Iraq without delay. 
  An INA correspondent in Cairo reported that the foreign 
minister explained to the Indian and Cypriot ministers that the 
Iraqi people, under the leadership of President Saddam Husayn, 
are determined to foil the embargo and the chapters of 
aggression. He also briefed them on the Iraqi people's efforts 
to reconstruct what was destroyed by the aggressors. 
  Dr. Nabil Najm, Iraq's permanent representative to the Arab 
League, attended the two meetings. 

</TEXT>

