<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Libyan, Thai Ministers Discuss Ties </H4>

<F P=102> BK0206130594 Bangkok Voice of Free Asia in Thai 1030 GMT 2 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0206130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Voice of Free Asia </F>
<F P=105>  Thai </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] During his participation in the NAM [Nonaligned 
Movement] Intersummit Meeting in Cairo from 31 May to 2 June, 
[Thai] Foreign Minister Squadron Leader Prasong Sunsiri held a 
meeting with his Libyan counterpart to clarify the controversy 
over the Libyan Government's repatriation of Thai workers. He 
informed the Libyan foreign minister, who also came to Cairo to 
attend the nonaligned meeting, that the whole problem can be 
attributed to a misunderstanding among several concerned parties 
including the Thai mass media. Citing the vote Thailand cast 
for Libya at the World Health Organization, he told his Libyan 
counterpart that Thailand always supports Libya, adding that 
Thailand has never thought of making any false charges against 
that country. He said only two out of 60 Thai job placement 
firms were involved in sending Thai workers to Libya without 
government permission. He asked that the Libyan foreign 
minister clarify his country's policy toward Thai workers. 
  The Libyan foreign minister replied that as a matter of 
fact, 
Libya has no bias against Thai workers. Preventive measures 
against law violations have been applied to workers from all 
countries, not specifically Thailand. The Libyan people admire 
and praise Thai workers for their honesty, diligence, and 
workmanship, and learned about Thailand from them. 
  The Libyan foreign minister also proposed that the Thai 
Government open an embassy in Libya so that it can look after 
the 25,000 Thai workers there more closely and further 
strengthen bilateral ties. 
  Squadron Leader Prasong Sunsiri foreign minister replied 
that 
the proposal was accepted for serious consideration and hope 
that Thai workers in Libya will continue to contribute to the 
strengthening of the Thai-Libyan relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35722 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes107yy_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Bosnian Minister on Prospects for Peace </H4>

<F P=102> NC0206200894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1435 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0206200894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 Jun (MENA) -- Irfan Ljubijankic, foreign 
minister of Bosnia-Herzegovina, has praised Egypt's role and 
participation in the peace-keeping force in Sarajevo. He noted 
that any Arab and Islamic troops operating within the UN forces 
would be welcomed by his country, particularly after the 
withdrawal of some European troops from Bosnia. Ljubijankic 
expected peace keeping troops from Pakistan, Malaysia, and 
Turkey to arrive in Bosnia. 
  Speaking at a news conference on the sidelines of the 
nonaligned foreign ministers' meeting currently being held in 
Cairo, Ljubijankic added that Bosnia had been reluctant to 
accept a comprehensive cease-fire for fear that the Serbs might 
use the truce to legalize their occupation of Bosnian territory 
and impose a fait-accompli by force. He pointed out that 
Bosnia's acceptance of the European peace plan is conditional on 
ascertaining that the refugees who fled war-stricken Bosnian 
cities would return home. He added: Their return is one of our 
main conditions for accepting the plan. Their return would mean 
a rejection of the tendency to acquire territory by force, he 
added, noting that the return of Muslim refugees to their homes 
would solve the problem. 
  Asked about the prospects for the survival of the federation 
between Muslims and Croats in Bosnia, he said that there are 
cooperation and long-standing common interests between the two 
sides, even if there is no love lost between them. He noted 
that this federation is a new development in the Bosnian war 
that has been proposed by the United States, and it is a good 
idea. He added: We have prepared everything on paper, but what 
counts is the actual implementation on the ground. 
  On his expectations about the chances that peace may be 
established in Bosnia in what is left of 1994, the Bosnian 
foreign minister said that officials would be happy if peace 
were achieved by the end of the year. But he expressed his 
belief that it is hard to persuade Serbia to conclude a peace 
agreement because its policy is based on the annexation of 
territory, and it is very difficult for the Serbs to give up 
this policy. He added that he hopes to meet with a reasonable 
Serbian official with whom he could talk. Noting that peace can 
be achieved with any degree of justice, he ruled out the 
possibility of achieving peace during this year. 
  The Bosnian official praised the efforts of the Nonaligned 
Movement in resolving the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina. He 
added that in the future his country will seek to gain full 
membership in the movement, noting that it is attending the 
current conference as a guest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35723 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes107yy_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NAM Foreign Ministers' Conference Ends in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Pakistani Minister Speaks on Kashmir </H4>

<F P=102> BK0306072094 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in Urdu 0200 
GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0306072094 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Urdu </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Pakistani] Foreign Minister Sardar Asif Ahmad Ali 
has asked the Nonaligned Movement [NAM] to play a role in 
negotiations between Pakistan and India to settle the Kashmir 
dispute. Addressing the NAM conference in Cairo, the foreign 
minister said Pakistan would like NAM to set up an inspection 
committee and urged NAM group to visit occupied Kashmir to 
observe human rights violations there, where half a million 
Indian troops suppressing an uprising for freedom by the 
Kashmiri people. He also proposed that a group of NAM countries 
be constituted to facilitate a process of peaceful negotiations 
to resolve the Kashmir dispute. The foreign minister said 
Pakistan is prepared to talk about Kashmir and whenever India 
shows a willingness to find a solution to the Kashmir dispute, 
the matter can be resolved. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

