<F P=100> Islamic Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Foreign Minister Views New Peace Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Foreign Minister Views New Peace Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0206111594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1010 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0206111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 Jun (MENA) -- Bosnian Foreign Minister 
Irfan Ljubijankic has stated that the International Conference 
Organization's liaison group at its meeting yesterday evening 
endorsed a peace plan for Bosnia submitted by Malaysia. In a 
statement made after his meeting with Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
today, he said that this plan will be issued as a separate 
resolution on Bosnia calling for an international peace 
conference under UN auspices. 
  Ljubijankic expressed his hope that this resolution will 
enjoy international support, particularly because it receives 
major support from the Nonaligned Movement and the Islamic 
countries. 
  Discussing the statement released by the Yugoslav Foreign 
Ministry regarding Egypt's refusal to invite Serbia and 
Montenegro to attend the conference, Ljubijankic said that 
Serbia is an aggressive country and it is only natural not to 
invite it to attend this gathering. He noted that the refusal 
to send an invitation was in line with the agreement reached 
among the nonaligned countries in New York. He said that there 
is an agreement among these countries not to invite Serbia. The 
proof of this is that none of the conference committees raised 
the issue, he said. 
  Ljubijankic said that he held amicable talks with Musa on 
the 
situation in Bosnia and the topics on the summit's agenda. He 
pointed out that Musa affirmed Egypt's support for Bosnia, 
noting that an agreement was reached to open an Egyptian Embassy 
in Sarajevo. He expressed his satisfaction that his country was 
invited to participate in the Nonaligned Movement Conference. 
He said that Bosnia is the legal heir of the former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35733 </DOCNO>
