<H3> <TI>   Doctors Confine 'Arafat to Bed, Order `Total Rest' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Doctors Confine 'Arafat to Bed, Order `Total Rest' </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Suha 'Arafat: 'Arafat in `Good Health' </H4>

<F P=102> NC0206183394 London MBC Television in Arabic 1813 GMT 2 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0206183394 </F>
<F P=104>  London MBC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Suha 'Arafat, wife of PLO Chairman </F>
Yasir 'Arafat, in Tunis by Nidal Qabalan in London on 2 June -- 
recorded] 
  [Text] [Mrs. 'Arafat] First of all, I would like to thank 
MBC for its interest in Abu-'Ammar's [Yasir 'Arafat] health. I 
assure you that there is no call for concern. Abu-'Ammar is in 
good health. He is only somewhat exhausted and has the flu; 
that is all there is to it. He will resume activity tonight. 
He is just a little tired. It is a very mild case of influenza. 
  Brother Nidal, you have noticed that for two weeks -- after 
the issue of his statement about jihad in Johannesburg -- there 
has been a series of rumors about Abu-'Ammar, his family, and 
about his illness. Now there is another rumor that he has been, 
or will be, taken to the hospital in Amman. 
  [Qabalan] Then the illness you say the Palestinian president 
has overcome will not affect his commitments, engagements, and 
his forthcoming visit to Jericho in the near future? 
  [Mrs. 'Arafat] Reassure our people inside that Abu-'Ammar 
will be on time. He is in good health. There is absolutely no 
call for concern. 
  [Qabalan] Mrs. 'Arafat, thank you. 

</TEXT>

