<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jordan's View of Palestinians Called `Obstacle' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jordan's View of Palestinians Called `Obstacle' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0206132494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 2 Jun 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> PM0206132494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mahmud Abu-'Id: "Palestinian Official Tells </F>
AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT: Jordan Not Dealing With Us as Economic 
Partner; `Commission-Seekers' Biggest Threat to the Palestinian 
Entity"] 
  [Excerpts] Amman, Jerusalem -- Commenting on the draft 
Palestinian-Jordanian agreement, Ibrahim Abu-'Ayyash, member of 
the Palestine Central Council and the Palestine National 
Council, has said in a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the 
agreement between the two sides is necessary and important. But 
the main obstacle lies in the nature of the Jordanian side's 
view of the Palestinians, which I believe does not regard the 
two sides as equal partners, but, rather, as a superior and a 
subordinate. 
  Abu-'Ayyash said that the nature of this view is worrying 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat, and that the main problem 
is that "they continue to talk to us on the basis that we are 
part of Jordan, not on the basis of our independence." [passage 
omitted] 
  Furthermore, Abu-'Ayyash said that the transitional phase 
involves great dangers, especially in view of rumors that 
Palestinian officials have become agents for international 
companies to distribute their commodities in the areas 
controlled by the Palestinian authority -- a phenomenon now 
known as the "commission-seekers" phenomenon. 
  In this context Abu-'Ayyash said: "Regrettably, rumors have 
cited names of figures close to Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat." However, he added: "Nevertheless, matters are still 
within the framework of rumors. But the important thing is for 
the Palestinian leadership to understand the seriousness of the 
stage ahead and thus not link its destiny with Israel, but with 
the Arab states." 
  He pointed out that the biggest threat to the new 
Palestinian 
entity is those who are trying to be clever. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

