<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa: Yemeni Unity by Force `Unacceptable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa: Yemeni Unity by Force `Unacceptable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0206145694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1305 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0206145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 Jun (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa has 
explained that the UN Security Council resolution pertaining to 
a cease-fire in Yemen is a "resolution that deals with the 
tragic situation of a nation whose northern and southern parts 
are fighting each other, namely an unacceptable situation." 
  Commenting further on the Security Council resolution, he 
explained that Egypt was one of the countries that sought this 
resolution because it is totally unacceptable to talk of unity 
by force. He added that it is very doubtful that a unity 
brought about by force can continue even if one of the warring 
factions defeats the other. He explained: "It is a very 
serious matter and would constitute an unacceptable precedent." 
  Asked what he thinks will happen if the Security Council 
resolution is not implemented, Musa said: "If the resolution is 
not implemented, we will handle things as they come." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

