<H3> <TI>   Resignation of U.S. Ambassador to Israel Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resignation of U.S. Ambassador to Israel Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0206133694 </F>
<F P=103> NC0206133694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] Beirut AL-SAFIR in Arabic in its 21 May 
issue features a straightforward 250-word report on page 1 
citing REUTER, AFP, AP, and UPI on the resignation of U.S. 
Ambassador to Israel Edward Djerejian. The report says that 
Djerejian decided to resign because he was excluded by the State 
Department from the decisionmaking process in the Syrian-Israeli 
track of the peace negotiations. The report cites a university 
source in Washington as saying that Djerejian will resign to 
assume a new position at Rice University in Houston as director 
of the James A. Baker Institute for Public Policy. The report 
notes that a spokesman at the U.S. Embassy in Tel Aviv said that 
Djerejian is resigning for personal and family reasons. 
  Beirut AL-DIYAR in Arabic in its 23 May issue carries a 
300-word straightforward report on page 14 citing AFP. The 
report notes that the State Department has denied the Israeli 
newspapers' claims that Djerejian resigned because he was 
"excluded" from the peace process. 
  Beirut AL-NAHAR in Arabic in its 20 May issue carries a 
150-word straightforward report on page 1 citing REUTER as 
saying that Djerejian decided to leave his post after only six 
months to assume a post at Rice University. The report states 
that Djerejian may work as a political adviser to James Baker 
should Baker decide to run for president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

