<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prithvi To Be Tested `During Next 48 Hours' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prithvi To Be Tested `During Next 48 Hours' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0206115294 Hong Kong AFP in English 1137 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0206115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi, June 2 (AFP) -- The Indian Army began the 
countdown Thursday for the first "user trial" of the home-built 
Prithvi surface-to-surface missile, whose possible deployment 
has aroused US concern, reports said here. 
  Prithvi, or Earth, which has a range of 250 kilometres (156 
miles), would be tested during the next 48 hours, the Press 
Trust of India (PTI) quoted unnamed defence sources here as 
saying. 
  A spokesman for the defence ministry here confirmed that 
preparations had begun for the trial, which was postponed from 
May 15 until Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao's return from a 
visit to the United States. 
  "The test will be carried out provided all systems are found 
to be working well and there are no last-minute snags," the 
spokesman said. 
  Top army experts and defence scientists have reached the 
test 
site at Chandipur-on-Sea in the eastern coastal state of Orissa, 
PTI said. 
  The missile has been successfully tested several times by 
the 
Department of Defence Production, but it would be the first 
"user-trial" ahead of its possible mass-production for 
deployment in the army. 
  US Ambassador-Designate Frank Wisner has urged New Delhi to 
reconsider deploying the missile. 
  Washington has voiced fears that India's missile programme 
might lead to another arms race between India and arch rival 
Pakistan, with whom it has fought three wars since 1947. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35781 </DOCNO>
