<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hamas Issues Leaflet on Jerusalem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hamas Issues Leaflet on Jerusalem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0606073294 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0405 GMT 6 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0606073294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Palestinian leaders in the territories are focusing 
efforts on East Jerusalem, mainly in a bid to lift the closure 
which has separated the city from the rest of the territories. 
Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] has distributed a leaflet 
in the territories calling for an exacerbation of the battle 
until Jerusalem is liberated. Our correspondent Moti Amir 
reports: 
  [Begin Amir recording] A senior Palestinian source stressed 
yesterday that PLO supporters will focus their political 
activity on the issue of East Jerusalem. The source stressed 
that the Palestinians will not remain silent in the face of 
demonstrations by the Israeli right wing, such as that organized 
by the Likud yesterday outside the Old City's walls. Faysal 
al-Husayni will hold a discussion on Jerusalem this afternoon at 
the Orient House building and report on the latest steps taken 
by the Israeli Government against Palestinian institutions in 
the eastern part of the city. 
  Hamas has also exhorted its followers to put an emphasis on 
the struggle over Jerusalem. In a special leaflet distributed 
in the territories yesterday, 'Izz-al-Din al-Qassam members were 
called upon to step up activities against Israel until what the 
leaflet described as the liberation of all of the homeland, 
including Jerusalem. 
  The Palestinian source explained that the PLO will now 
concentrate its efforts on lifting the closure on East 
Jerusalem, which has severed the city from the territories. 
  In discussions held yesterday by Palestinian self-government 
officials in the Gaza Strip and Jericho, the police commanders 
in both areas expressed praise for the rapid organization of the 
Palestinian forces and noted that they believe the police are 
operating smoothly and satisfactorily despite all the 
difficulties. 
  General 'Abd-al-Razzaq al-Yahya, who was head of the 
Palestinian delegation on security affairs in the peace 
negotiations, crossed through the Rafah border terminal into the 
Gaza Strip yesterday. Gen. al-Yahya will be in charge of public 
security in the autonomous areas, together with Police Commander 
Nasr Yusuf. 
  An advance force of 36 Palestinian intelligence officers has 
arrived in Jericho. The men received training in intelligence 
work in Egypt, Algeria, and Tunis. They will mainly be in 
charge of the PLO's military intelligence. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

