<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-108 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources: No `Dramatic' Rise in 1995 Defense Spending </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sources: No `Dramatic' Rise in 1995 Defense Spending </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0506125394 Islamabad THE NEWS in English 5 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BK0506125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad THE NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad -- Pakistan government has no intentions 
of dramatically increasing its defence budget for the next 
financial year, highly placed government sources told this 
correspondent on Saturday. 
  "We have no intention of increasing the defence budget in 
real terms. 
  This should not be taken to mean that we do not take the 
country's defence requirements seriously but we cannot afford to 
be irresponsible with our finance," these sources said. 
  Experts were expecting a heavy raise in Pakistan's defence 
budget this year, after India increased its defence spending by 
a whooping 29 per cent in its budget for fiscal 1994-95, 
starting April 1, 1994. 
  "The extraordinary increase by India is basically a strategy 
to preserve a deterrent. However, unlike India we do not have 
the kind of resources to give such a massive raise in the 
defence budget," noted the source. 
  Islamabad has been applying a cut in real terms, that is 
after discounting inflation, on defence spending for the last 
three years. 
  In the Federal Budget for fiscal 1993-94, defence spending 
claimed Rs 89.1 billion [rupees] or about a third of the total 
budgeted expenditure. This was about two per cent increase over 
the previous year's revised estimate of Rs 87.4 billion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

