<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Majali Briefs House on State of Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Majali Briefs House on State of Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0506210094 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 2000 GMT 5 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0506210094 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In a special session with the Speaker and members 
of the House of Representatives in the Pictures Hall at the 
parliament building today, Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam 
al-Majali reviewed a number of national and foreign issues. Dr. 
al-Majali also spoke about where the government stood on 
regional developments. 
  House Speaker Tahir al-Masri, told journalists after the 
meeting that one of the topics that figured prominently at the 
session was the Jordanian-Palestinian relationship. The prime 
minister, said al-Masri, underscored the importance of these 
ties and Jordan's keenness to maintain coordination that 
advances, first, the Palestinian cause and the new Palestinian 
situation and, second, the interests of the two countries. 
  The prime minister said the present level of coordination 
fell short of expectations and has not been as effective as we 
would have liked. The prime minister, added al-Masri, stressed 
that Jordan was committed to a role of support for the 
Palestinian cause, no matter what the obstacles, and free from 
any ambitions or any attempt to dominate. 
  The prime minister, according to al-Masri, had paid tribute 
to Jordanian-Egyptian relations. He emphasized that the 
meetings of the Higher Jordanian-Egyptian Committee had helped 
solidify these ties. Relations with Syria also have a special 
significance, given that the two countries' stands were similar 
and complementary on the negotiations and the potential for 
bilateral and regional cooperation. 
  The prime minister also said at the session that Jordan 
stood 
for a halt to fighting in brotherly Yemen and a hands-off 
policy. Jordan was against taking sides and for legitimacy and 
unity. Al- Masri further noted that the prime minister had 
vigorously denied 'Ali Salim al-Bid's contention that Jordan was 
extending assistance to the Yemeni Government in Sanaa. He 
regretted that such an unjust charge should have been made by 
al-Bid against Jordan, which had given his majesty the king a 
mandate to take whatever measures he deemed would advance 
Yemen's unity. All that Jordan did was to airlift Jordanian and 
other nationals from Yemen on purely humanitarian grounds to 
spare them the risks involved in a war situation, explained the 
house speaker. 
  The prime minister, went on al-Masri, reported to the 
deputies on the state of the negotiations between Jordan and 
Israel and the agenda of the meeting to be held in Washington 
tomorrow. He stressed that Jordan adheres to its declared 
constants. There will not be a separate deal on the Jordanian 
front, the prime minister was quoted as emphasizing by the house 
speaker. 

</TEXT>

