<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Denies Sending Weapons to Sanaa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Denies Sending Weapons to Sanaa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0506130794 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 5 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0506130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Randah Habib in Amman] </F>
  [Text] Jordanian Prime Minister 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali has 
categorically denied Aden's accusation that Jordan is sending 
weapons to Sanaa, saying that the accusation conflicts with 
Jordan's support for dialogue in Yemen. Al-Majali asserted that 
Jordan has never thought of sending weapons to any side in Yemen 
and reiterated that Jordan does not support one side against the 
other, and that it opposes infighting and believes in dialogue 
to resolve the bloody crisis in that country. 
  Al-Majli also said that Jordan supports unity and legitimacy 
in Yemen, that the unity was carried out as a result of the 
Yemeni people's decision, and that Jordan will continue to 
believe in that unless the Yemeni people want otherwise. 
  With regard to planes, al-Majali said that Amman had sent 
Royal Jordanian aircraft, and C-130 transportation planes to 
evacuate its nationals from Yemen, as well as other European and 
Asian nationals on humanitarian grounds, and that these aircraft 
carried nothing other than passengers. 

</TEXT>

