<H3> <TI>   Beilin Proposes `Chillier' Relations With Italy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beilin Proposes `Chillier' Relations With Italy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0506184694 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0506184694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen] </F>
  [Excerpt] Italian Foreign Minister Antonio Martino would 
like to visit Israel soon in order to settle matters in the wake 
of the appointment of three neofascist ministers to Silvio 
Berlusconi's new government. The new government has yet to 
receive Israel's blessing. Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin 
is demanding that Israel cool its ties with Italy in the wake of 
the appointments. Italy's Jewish community is opposed to such a 
move. Our political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen reports on 
the controversy: 
  [Begin recording] [Rosen] Today the world should hear 
Israel loud and clear, Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin said. 
He suggests taking resolute steps toward chillier relations 
with Italy following the appointment of neofascist ministers to 
the Berlusconi cabinet. 
  Israel did not applaud Italy's political upheaval, and Rabin 
has deliberately refrained from congratulating the new prime 
minister. Beilin has already ordered a freeze on the departure 
of a delegation to a cultural conference. 
  [Beilin] Obviously, we cannot take a light view of this. It 
is the first time a party with neofascist elements is 
participating in a European government. 
  [Rosen] Beilin's adamant position is opposed by many Italian 
Jews, as well as members of the professional Foreign Ministry 
echelons who believe Israel should wait and judge the neofascist 
ministers on the basis of their actions and pronouncements as of 
now. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

