<DOCNO> FBIS4-35921 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes107_o_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials `Shocked' by Djerejian Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials `Shocked' by Djerejian Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0206165094 Kuwait AL-QABAS in Arabic 21 May 94 p 24 </F>
<F P=103> JN0206165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait AL-QABAS </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nabih al-Barji in Beirut] </F>
  [Text] Political sources close to Damascus in Beirut have 
said that Syrian officials were shocked by the decision of 
Edward Djerejian, the U.S. ambassador in Tel Aviv, to leave his 
post in order to pursue a possible election campaign that will 
be led by former U.S. Secretary of State James Baker to face 
U.S. President Bill Clinton in the White House battle. 
  Syrian officials had thought that the appointment of 
Djerejian, who had served as ambassador in Damascus before he 
was appointed assistant U.S. secretary of state for Middle 
Eastern affairs -- to head the U.S. diplomatic mission in Tel 
Aviv was a positive signal that the Clinton administration wants 
this seasoned diplomat, who is an expert on the Middle East, to 
energize Israel's position toward a peaceful formula with Syria 
that is thought to be a central formula for a comprehensive 
settlement in the region. 
  Those officials, however, have immediately noticed that 
there 
are concerted efforts to keep Djerejian away from any important 
activities. In fact, U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher 
almost ignored him completely in his efforts to approximate 
views between the Syrian and Israeli governments. 
  Damascus thinks that the decision of Djerejian -- who had 
faced a personal predicament from which resignation was the only 
way out -- gives further evidence of the efficiency of the 
attack launched by the Jewish lobby in the United States to 
prevent the Clinton administration from playing a balanced role 
in advancing the negotiating process. 
  The Syrian officials are very tense when they view the 
fierce 
method adopted by the Jewish lobby to contain President Clinton, 
as signs of another presidential election campaign have drawn 
near. Some members of the lobby had previously made it public 
that they object to giving Syria an influential role in 
crystallizing the structure of the forthcoming regional order. 
  Those sources think that Dennis Ross, the U.S. negotiation 
coordinator, and Martin Indyk, the official in charge of the 
Middle East in the National Security Council, have managed to 
close in on Djerejian. 
  In fact, Syrian fears go farther than this. Strobe Talbott, 
the deputy secretary of state who is known for his relatively 
balanced view of the Middle East crisis, is being totally 
ignored. Syrian officials have noticed some signs of a trend in 
the U.S. State Department and the National Security Council -- 
without casting doubt on President Clinton and Secretary of 
State Christopher -- to dismantle the diplomatic formula 
launched by the former U.S. Secretary of State James Baker and 
on whose basis the Syrians had accepted to attend the peace 
conference in Madrid in October 1991. 
  The Madrid formula depends on Security Council Resolutions 
242 and 338 which were bypassed when the Gaza-Jericho agreement 
was signed, according to Syria's view of this agreement. 
  Now that Djerejian is absent from the scene, it seems that 
all doors are wide open to Jewish influence in the circles at 
which U.S. policies on the Middle East are drawn up. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-35922 </DOCNO>
