<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Bid Accuses Sanaa of Starting War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Bid Accuses Sanaa of Starting War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0506133794 Kuwait Radio Kuwait in Arabic 1000 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0506133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait Radio Kuwait </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] 'Ali Salim al-Bid, Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] 
secretary general, said that it was Sanaa that started the war 
in Yemen and that the war was forcibly imposed on the south. 
  In an interview he gave to AL-QABAS newspaper reporter 
'Abd-al-Salam al-'Awadi in Mukalla, which was published today, 
Al-Bid said that the southerners entered the union willingly 
with sound convictions and dealt with it in the same sound 
spirit and with democratic means. 
  'Ali Salim al-Bid said that integration did not take place 
between the two parts of Yemen due to the existence of two types 
of upbringing, two types of thought, two types of mentality and 
two different methods. He said that the southerners wanted 
democratic pluralism in a way that conformed with the spirit of 
the age in the shadow of security, stability, and unity. 
  The YSP secretary general affirmed that southerners were 
treated as third- or fourth-class citizens in the union. He 
said that we have discovered from the way Sanaa treated us that 
we were two peoples, not one. 
  'Ali Salim al-Bid stressed that the war that was taking 
place 
in Yemen affected the security and stability of the Gulf region 
and the interests of its peoples. He called on the Arab 
countries to work in the Yemeni people's interests, emphasizing 
that the continuation of the civil war in Yemen was not in the 
interests of the region as a whole. 
  'Ali Salim al-Bid said the announcement of the cessation of 
the south from the north has come for the benefit of Yemen, to 
prevent it from being divided into mini-states if the war, in 
which there would be no victor or vanquished, continues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

